iness with their religious orders and the strictures of the church hierarchy. At a time when questions of gender, religion, race, and sexuality are provoking intense debate within Catholicism and other Christian traditions, and when religion is frequently invoked in political rhetoric, these stories provide a vital corrective to our contemporary understanding of the role of women and nuns in the Roman Catholic Church.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aNunsvBiography. 0aWomen in the Catholic Church. 4aGeneral Interest : Fiction. 4aGeneral Interest : Memoir. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Christian Life / Women's Issues.2bisacsh1 aBirch-Conery, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreslin, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelRosso, Jeana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDolan, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Patricia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEicke, Leigh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGanim, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGramick, Jeannine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanis, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKothe, Ana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarie, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolesky-Poz, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontley, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrissey, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https